Scenario: A 39-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of acute-onset left-sided chest pain, which began approximately 8 hours prior to presentation, last night. The pain is described as sharp and constant, rating 7-8 out of 10 in severity, and is aggravated by lying down and taking a deep breath, with relief noted when not supine. The pain does not radiate. Associated symptoms include lightheadedness, dyspnea that began concurrently with the chest pain, mild palpitations, and diaphoresis attributed to the breathing difficulty. He also reports a perceived swelling in his neck, though denies neck pain or any recent trauma. He denies loss of consciousness, nausea, vomiting, fever, chills, abdominal pain, urinary or bowel problems, cough, hemoptysis, wheezing, or noisy breathing unless his dyspnea is severe. The pain started while moving furniture, but he denies any specific injury. He reports no prior similar episodes. His past medical history is unremarkable, with no known chronic conditions, prior hospitalizations, or surgeries. He takes no regular medications and has no known drug allergies, and his immunizations are up to date. Socially, he lives alone in an apartment and works as an accountant. He has a significant smoking history of one pack per day for 10-15 years, occasionally uses cannabis (approximately 5 mg per week), and consumes alcohol at a rate of 1-2 drinks daily, totaling about 10 drinks per week. He denies any other illicit or intravenous drug use. His diet consists of healthy dinners but frequent restaurant lunches, and he exercises regularly, running for 30 minutes every other day. Family history is notable for his father experiencing a myocardial infarction at age 45 and having a history of hypercholesterolemia; there is no family history of stroke or cancer.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aaj aapko kya takleef hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: हाँ, मुझे सीने में बहुत दर्द हो रहा है, इसलिए मैंने सोचा कि मुझे इसे दिखाना चाहिए।

Scenario: A 39-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of acute-onset left-sided chest pain, which began approximately 8 hours prior to presentation, last night. The pain is described as sharp and constant, rating 7-8 out of 10 in severity, and is aggravated by lying down and taking a deep breath, with relief noted when not supine. The pain does not radiate. Associated symptoms include lightheadedness, dyspnea that began concurrently with the chest pain, mild palpitations, and diaphoresis attributed to the breathing difficulty. He also reports a perceived swelling in his neck, though denies neck pain or any recent trauma. He denies loss of consciousness, nausea, vomiting, fever, chills, abdominal pain, urinary or bowel problems, cough, hemoptysis, wheezing, or noisy breathing unless his dyspnea is severe. The pain started while moving furniture, but he denies any specific injury. He reports no prior similar episodes. His past medical history is unremarkable, with no known chronic conditions, prior hospitalizations, or surgeries. He takes no regular medications and has no known drug allergies, and his immunizations are up to date. Socially, he lives alone in an apartment and works as an accountant. He has a significant smoking history of one pack per day for 10-15 years, occasionally uses cannabis (approximately 5 mg per week), and consumes alcohol at a rate of 1-2 drinks daily, totaling about 10 drinks per week. He denies any other illicit or intravenous drug use. His diet consists of healthy dinners but frequent restaurant lunches, and he exercises regularly, running for 30 minutes every other day. Family history is notable for his father experiencing a myocardial infarction at age 45 and having a history of hypercholesterolemia; there is no family history of stroke or cancer.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Kya aapko gardan mein koi dard hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नहीं।

Associated symptoms include lightheadedness, dyspnea that began concurrently with the chest pain, mild palpitations, and diaphoresis attributed to the breathing difficulty. He also reports a perceived swelling in his neck, though denies neck pain or any recent trauma. He denies loss of consciousness, nausea, vomiting, fever, chills, abdominal pain, urinary or bowel problems, cough, hemoptysis, wheezing, or noisy breathing unless his dyspnea is severe. The pain started while moving furniture, but he denies any specific injury. He reports no prior similar episodes. His past medical history is unremarkable, with no known chronic conditions, prior hospitalizations, or surgeries. He takes no regular medications and has no known drug allergies, and his immunizations are up to date. Socially, he lives alone in an apartment and works as an accountant. He has a significant smoking history of one pack per day for 10-15 years, occasionally uses cannabis (approximately 5 mg per week), and consumes alcohol at a rate of 1-2 drinks daily, totaling about 10 drinks per week. He denies any other illicit or intravenous drug use. His diet consists of healthy dinners but frequent restaurant lunches, and he exercises regularly, running for 30 minutes every other day. Family history is notable for his father experiencing a myocardial infarction at age 45 and having a history of hypercholesterolemia; there is no family history of stroke or cancer.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Kya aapne pehle kabhi IV drugs use ki hain?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नहीं।

Scenario: A 40-year-old male, a city bus driver, presents with a chief complaint of acute-onset left-sided chest pain that began approximately 30 minutes prior to presentation while shoveling his driveway. The pain is described as dull and pressure-like, rated 7/10 in severity, and has been progressively worsening since its onset. It is localized to the left chest and does not radiate. Aggravating factors include movement, walking, and lying down, with no reported alleviating factors. Associated symptoms include shortness of breath, which started concurrently with the chest pain, and a subjective feeling of being hot, with a measured temperature of 38°C. He also reports palpitations, noting his heart feels like it is beating faster than usual, similar to when playing sports. He denies nausea, vomiting, chills, leg or feet swelling, increased fatigue, dizziness, fainting, or skin rashes. He reports a rugby tackle yesterday but states his chest felt fine afterward, and the pain onset was distinct. He denies recent travel or sick contacts. He notes a self-resolving runny nose a few weeks prior but no recent cough or sore throat. His past medical history is significant for hypertension and hypercholesterolemia, for which he takes Lisinopril and Rosuvastatin, along with a multivitamin. He reports no known drug allergies, prior hospitalizations, or surgeries. Social history reveals he lives in a house with his parents, exercises by running on Sundays, and describes his diet as fairly balanced despite frequent dining out. He has a 20-year history of smoking approximately 0.5-1 pack of cigarettes daily. He denies alcohol use but admits to using crystal meth for the past 7 years, typically a couple of times a month, with his last use being 6 days ago. Family history is negative for heart attack or cancers.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aaj aap yahan kis wajah se aaye hain?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: हाँ, मुझे सीने में दर्द हो रहा है।

Scenario: A male patient presents with a chief complaint of progressively worsening breathlessness over the past two months, insidious in onset. He reports exertional dyspnea, experiencing significant shortness of breath after walking more than 50 meters, a distance he could manage without difficulty three months prior. He also describes orthopnea, gasping for air when lying flat, which is worse at night and partially relieved by stacking pillows. He can climb only 3-4 steps before becoming breathless. Associated symptoms include an intermittent cough, sometimes producing frothy sputum, and increasing fatigue throughout the day. He also notes bilateral lower extremity swelling, which began approximately two months ago, concurrent with the onset of his dyspnea. He denies constant cough, paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea, sore throat, runny nose, chest pain, dizziness, headache, nausea, vomiting, fevers, chills, night sweats, changes in bowel movements, hemoptysis, weight loss, changes in appetite, recent infections, recent travel, or exposure to tuberculosis, fumes, dust, or animals. His past medical history is significant for hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and hyperlipidemia, for which he takes aspirin, ramipril, and simvastatin. He suffered a myocardial infarction four years ago, managed with coronary stenting, and denies similar symptoms since that event. He has no known drug or environmental allergies. Socially, he works as a cashier, and his symptoms are impacting his ability to perform his job, particularly with prolonged standing or exertion. He lives alone in an apartment with no reported environmental exposures. He is an ex-smoker, having smoked 10 cigarettes per day for 40 years (40 pack-years), but denies current smoking, alcohol, or recreational drug use. He describes his diet as not well-balanced and reports a decrease in his exercise and activity levels over the past two months. Family history is notable for his father who died of a heart attack at age 60.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aaj aap yahan kis wajah se aaye hain?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: हाँ, मुझे बस साँस लेने में दिक्कत हो रही है और यह बढ़ती जा रही है, इसलिए मैं इसे दिखाना चाहता था।

He reports exertional dyspnea, experiencing significant shortness of breath after walking more than 50 meters, a distance he could manage without difficulty three months prior. He also describes orthopnea, gasping for air when lying flat, which is worse at night and partially relieved by stacking pillows. He can climb only 3-4 steps before becoming breathless. Associated symptoms include an intermittent cough, sometimes producing frothy sputum, and increasing fatigue throughout the day. He also notes bilateral lower extremity swelling, which began approximately two months ago, concurrent with the onset of his dyspnea. He denies constant cough, paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea, sore throat, runny nose, chest pain, dizziness, headache, nausea, vomiting, fevers, chills, night sweats, changes in bowel movements, hemoptysis, weight loss, changes in appetite, recent infections, recent travel, or exposure to tuberculosis, fumes, dust, or animals. His past medical history is significant for hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and hyperlipidemia, for which he takes aspirin, ramipril, and simvastatin. He suffered a myocardial infarction four years ago, managed with coronary stenting, and denies similar symptoms since that event. He has no known drug or environmental allergies. Socially, he works as a cashier, and his symptoms are impacting his ability to perform his job, particularly with prolonged standing or exertion. He lives alone in an apartment with no reported environmental exposures. He is an ex-smoker, having smoked 10 cigarettes per day for 40 years (40 pack-years), but denies current smoking, alcohol, or recreational drug use. He describes his diet as not well-balanced and reports a decrease in his exercise and activity levels over the past two months. Family history is notable for his father who died of a heart attack at age 60.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aap kitni seedhiyan chadhne ke baad saans phoolna shuru ho jaata hai, kya aap bata sakte hain?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: मैं कहूंगा कि लगभग तीन-चौथाई।

Scenario: A male patient presents with a chief complaint of progressively worsening breathlessness over the past two months, insidious in onset. He reports exertional dyspnea, experiencing significant shortness of breath after walking more than 50 meters, a distance he could manage without difficulty three months prior. He also describes orthopnea, gasping for air when lying flat, which is worse at night and partially relieved by stacking pillows. He can climb only 3-4 steps before becoming breathless. Associated symptoms include an intermittent cough, sometimes producing frothy sputum, and increasing fatigue throughout the day. He also notes bilateral lower extremity swelling, which began approximately two months ago, concurrent with the onset of his dyspnea. He denies constant cough, paroxysmal nocturnal dyspnea, sore throat, runny nose, chest pain, dizziness, headache, nausea, vomiting, fevers, chills, night sweats, changes in bowel movements, hemoptysis, weight loss, changes in appetite, recent infections, recent travel, or exposure to tuberculosis, fumes, dust, or animals. His past medical history is significant for hypertension, diabetes mellitus, and hyperlipidemia, for which he takes aspirin, ramipril, and simvastatin. He suffered a myocardial infarction four years ago, managed with coronary stenting, and denies similar symptoms since that event. He has no known drug or environmental allergies. Socially, he works as a cashier, and his symptoms are impacting his ability to perform his job, particularly with prolonged standing or exertion. He lives alone in an apartment with no reported environmental exposures. He is an ex-smoker, having smoked 10 cigarettes per day for 40 years (40 pack-years), but denies current smoking, alcohol, or recreational drug use. He describes his diet as not well-balanced and reports a decrease in his exercise and activity levels over the past two months. Family history is notable for his father who died of a heart attack at age 60.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aapko kisi bhi dava se koi allergy to nahi hai na?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नहीं।

Scenario: The patient presents with a chief complaint of left-sided chest pain, experienced intermittently over the past two weeks. The history of present illness reveals an insidious onset of sharp, localized chest discomfort on the left side, without radiation. Episodes typically last 20-30 minutes and have occurred 2-3 times over the two-week period, with a self-rated severity of 4/10. The pain is not constant but comes and goes, and has remained consistent in intensity and frequency since its onset. The patient notes that episodes most frequently occur while at work or driving. Attempts to alleviate the pain with Advil, Tylenol, and Tums have been unsuccessful, with the pain resolving spontaneously. Denied associated symptoms include nausea, vomiting, difficulty breathing, fevers, or heartburn. The patient reports no prior similar episodes and acknowledges increased personal stress over the past two years due to a marital separation. Past medical history is significant for being previously healthy, with no chronic conditions such as hypertension or hypercholesterolemia (though cholesterol has never been tested). The patient takes no regular medications and reports no known allergies. There is no history of recent contact with sick individuals or travel outside of Canada. Social history indicates current smoking of 0.5-1 pack of cigarettes per day, a reduction from a previous 1 pack per day, with ongoing efforts to quit. Alcohol consumption is limited to 1-2 glasses of wine on weekends, and illicit drug use is denied. The patient engages in regular exercise, running or cycling 3-4 days per week, without experiencing chest pain during these activities. Family history is notable for the patient's father experiencing a heart attack at age 60 last year.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aapko shayad chest mein dard ho raha hai.
Patient_Responses_Hindi: हाँ, तो यह सीने में दर्द पिछले कुछ हफ़्तों से हो रहा है।

Scenario: The patient presents with a chief complaint of left-sided chest pain, experienced intermittently over the past two weeks. Alcohol consumption is limited to 1-2 glasses of wine on weekends, and illicit drug use is denied. The patient engages in regular exercise, running or cycling 3-4 days per week, without experiencing chest pain during these activities. Family history is notable for the patient's father experiencing a heart attack at age 60 last year.

Scenario: A 45-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a painful, swollen, and red lesion on his right ankle, which he initially described as a "rash" but clarified as more painful than rash-like. The patient reports the lesion appeared approximately one week ago, with pain developing yesterday. He describes the area as swollen, increasingly red, and "meaner" in appearance. He notes the presence of scabs, which he admits to scratching, and one of these scabs has since opened, leaking a "white stuff" (suggestive of purulent discharge) since the swelling began. The pain is exacerbated by walking and flexing the ankle but is relieved at rest. He reports feeling "hot" for the past 12 hours, and subjectively notes his right leg feels hotter than his left. He has also experienced a general feeling of being "crummy" for the last couple of weeks, with decreased energy today, increased hunger, and tiredness, which he attributes to stress and potentially poorly controlled diabetes. He denies difficulty breathing or chest pain. While he has a history of occasional diabetic ulcers and minor foot trauma due to poor foot care, he states this specific presentation is "strange looking" and unlike anything he has experienced before, though he does have a currently "doing alright" ulcer on his left heel. His past medical history is significant for poorly controlled Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus, with a last known A1C of approximately 9, for which he takes three oral medications (including Metformin and an unnamed "Sidas...something"), but is not on insulin and has stopped regularly monitoring his blood sugars. He also has a history of hypercholesterolemia, for which he takes Rosuvastatin, childhood asthma (currently asymptomatic), and chronic back pain for 10 years managed with Tylenol and Advil. He reports decreased sensation in his feet over the years but notes only a dull ache in the affected ankle area. He has a known penicillin allergy, manifesting as facial bloating and difficulty breathing as a child. His surgical history includes sinus surgery in his teens for sinusitis. Socially, he is a 45-year-old unemployed accountant, partially self-employed, living in town and seeing his children every two weeks. He smokes occasionally, increasing to approximately two packs per week recently due to stress, and consumes alcohol, averaging a 24-pack of beer per weekend, primarily on those days. Family history reveals a strong maternal predisposition to diabetes, hypertension, and hypercholesterolemia, while his paternal side is generally healthy, with one aunt having lung cancer, who was a heavy smoker.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: नमस्ते, तो मैं समझ रहा हूँ कि आपके पैर पर रैश (khujli/laali) है।
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नमस्ते डॉक्टर साहब, मैं 45 साल का पुरुष हूँ, मुझे अपने पैर पर एक पुराने दाने को लेकर चिंता हो रही है।

Scenario: A 45-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a painful, swollen, and red lesion on his right ankle, which he initially described as a "rash" but clarified as more painful than rash-like. The patient reports the lesion appeared approximately one week ago, with pain developing yesterday. He describes the area as swollen, increasingly red, and "meaner" in appearance. He notes the presence of scabs, which he admits to scratching, and one of these scabs has since opened, leaking a "white stuff" (suggestive of purulent discharge) since the swelling began. The pain is exacerbated by walking and flexing the ankle but is relieved at rest. He reports feeling "hot" for the past 12 hours, and subjectively notes his right leg feels hotter than his left. He has also experienced a general feeling of being "crummy" for the last couple of weeks, with decreased energy today, increased hunger, and tiredness, which he attributes to stress and potentially poorly controlled diabetes. He denies difficulty breathing or chest pain. While he has a history of occasional diabetic ulcers and minor foot trauma due to poor foot care, he states this specific presentation is "strange looking" and unlike anything he has experienced before, though he does have a currently "doing alright" ulcer on his left heel. His past medical history is significant for poorly controlled Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus, with a last known A1C of approximately 9, for which he takes three oral medications (including Metformin and an unnamed "Sidas...something"), but is not on insulin and has stopped regularly monitoring his blood sugars. He also has a history of hypercholesterolemia, for which he takes Rosuvastatin, childhood asthma (currently asymptomatic), and chronic back pain for 10 years managed with Tylenol and Advil. He reports decreased sensation in his feet over the years but notes only a dull ache in the affected ankle area. He has a known penicillin allergy, manifesting as facial bloating and difficulty breathing as a child. His surgical history includes sinus surgery in his teens for sinusitis. Socially, he is a 45-year-old unemployed accountant, partially self-employed, living in town and seeing his children every two weeks. He smokes occasionally, increasing to approximately two packs per week recently due to stress, and consumes alcohol, averaging a 24-pack of beer per weekend, primarily on those days. Family history reveals a strong maternal predisposition to diabetes, hypertension, and hypercholesterolemia, while his paternal side is generally healthy, with one aunt having lung cancer, who was a heavy smoker.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Kya aapko saans lene mein koi takleef hui hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: मेरे घर पर थर्मामीटर नहीं है।

He notes the presence of scabs, which he admits to scratching, and one of these scabs has since opened, leaking a "white stuff" (suggestive of purulent discharge) since the swelling began. The pain is exacerbated by walking and flexing the ankle but is relieved at rest. He reports feeling "hot" for the past 12 hours, and subjectively notes his right leg feels hotter than his left. He has also experienced a general feeling of being "crummy" for the last couple of weeks, with decreased energy today, increased hunger, and tiredness, which he attributes to stress and potentially poorly controlled diabetes. He denies difficulty breathing or chest pain. While he has a history of occasional diabetic ulcers and minor foot trauma due to poor foot care, he states this specific presentation is "strange looking" and unlike anything he has experienced before, though he does have a currently "doing alright" ulcer on his left heel. His past medical history is significant for poorly controlled Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus, with a last known A1C of approximately 9, for which he takes three oral medications (including Metformin and an unnamed "Sidas...something"), but is not on insulin and has stopped regularly monitoring his blood sugars. He also has a history of hypercholesterolemia, for which he takes Rosuvastatin, childhood asthma (currently asymptomatic), and chronic back pain for 10 years managed with Tylenol and Advil. He reports decreased sensation in his feet over the years but notes only a dull ache in the affected ankle area. He has a known penicillin allergy, manifesting as facial bloating and difficulty breathing as a child. His surgical history includes sinus surgery in his teens for sinusitis. Socially, he is a 45-year-old unemployed accountant, partially self-employed, living in town and seeing his children every two weeks. He smokes occasionally, increasing to approximately two packs per week recently due to stress, and consumes alcohol, averaging a 24-pack of beer per weekend, primarily on those days. Family history reveals a strong maternal predisposition to diabetes, hypertension, and hypercholesterolemia, while his paternal side is generally healthy, with one aunt having lung cancer, who was a heavy smoker.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Kya aapko kisi cheez se koi allergy hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नहीं नहीं, पर लगभग एक साल से ये समस्या है।

Scenario: A 45-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of a painful, swollen, and red lesion on his right ankle, which he initially described as a "rash" but clarified as more painful than rash-like. While he has a history of occasional diabetic ulcers and minor foot trauma due to poor foot care, he states this specific presentation is "strange looking" and unlike anything he has experienced before, though he does have a currently "doing alright" ulcer on his left heel. He also has a history of hypercholesterolemia, for which he takes Rosuvastatin, childhood asthma (currently asymptomatic), and chronic back pain for 10 years managed with Tylenol and Advil. He has a known penicillin allergy, manifesting as facial bloating and difficulty breathing as a child. His surgical history includes sinus surgery in his teens for sinusitis. Scenario: A female patient presents with a chief complaint of persistent nausea for approximately 9 days, describing it as constant but exacerbated in the mornings and by noxious odors. She reports associated emesis, occurring once or twice daily on "a lot of days" over the past 1-2 weeks. Concurrently, she notes increased urinary frequency, voiding every 1-2 hours, and occasionally waking at night to urinate, though she maintains full control and denies urgency or dysuria, attributing this to increased fluid intake due to perceived dehydration. She also reports mild abdominal cramping, initially thought to be menstrual, and amenorrhea, with her last menstrual period approximately six weeks ago, which is unusual for her typically regular cycle. She denies flu-like symptoms, headaches, fevers, muscle aches, cough, hematochezia, palpitations, or chest pain. Her past medical history is unremarkable, with no chronic conditions or current medications, aside from ineffective ginger chews for nausea. She reports a nickel allergy causing contact dermatitis but no food or medication allergies. Socially, she lives with a roommate, is a non-smoker, rarely consumes alcohol (last drink one month ago), and denies illicit drug use. She is sexually active with her boyfriend, using condoms for contraception, having previously discontinued oral contraceptives due to side effects of feeling "sick." Family history is notable only for paternal hypertension.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aaj aapko kya takleef hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: मुझे अभी हर समय मतली जैसा महसूस हो रहा है।

She reports associated emesis, occurring once or twice daily on "a lot of days" over the past 1-2 weeks. Concurrently, she notes increased urinary frequency, voiding every 1-2 hours, and occasionally waking at night to urinate, though she maintains full control and denies urgency or dysuria, attributing this to increased fluid intake due to perceived dehydration. She also reports mild abdominal cramping, initially thought to be menstrual, and amenorrhea, with her last menstrual period approximately six weeks ago, which is unusual for her typically regular cycle. She denies flu-like symptoms, headaches, fevers, muscle aches, cough, hematochezia, palpitations, or chest pain. Her past medical history is unremarkable, with no chronic conditions or current medications, aside from ineffective ginger chews for nausea. She reports a nickel allergy causing contact dermatitis but no food or medication allergies. Socially, she lives with a roommate, is a non-smoker, rarely consumes alcohol (last drink one month ago), and denies illicit drug use. She is sexually active with her boyfriend, using condoms for contraception, having previously discontinued oral contraceptives due to side effects of feeling "sick." Family history is notable only for paternal hypertension.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Kya aapko lagta hai ki aapka bathroom jaane par control hai ya aapko rokne mein mushkil hoti hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: हाँ, मैं इसे नियंत्रित कर सकता हूँ, बस थोड़ा असहज महसूस हो रहा है।

Scenario: A female patient presents to the Emergency Department with a chief complaint of right upper quadrant abdominal pain. Her history of present illness details an insidious onset of sharp, localized pain in the right upper quadrant, just below the lungs, approximately three days prior, occurring 30-60 minutes after lunch. The pain has progressively worsened, becoming significantly more severe in the last 3-4 hours before presentation, now rated 8/10 in intensity. It does not radiate and remains confined to the right upper quadrant. She reports associated nausea over the past few days, which is worse today, but denies any vomiting, blood in emesis, skin changes, rashes, changes in urinary habits (dysuria, color changes), or changes in bowel patterns (diarrhea, color changes, blood in stool). Her energy levels are decreased today due to the pain, and her appetite is also significantly reduced today, though it was previously normal. Over-the-counter Advil and Tylenol provided no significant relief. She recalls a similar episode of pain a few years ago that resolved spontaneously without medical intervention. Her past medical history is largely unremarkable, with no known drug allergies, no prescribed medications (though she occasionally takes over-the-counter antacids a couple of times a month for heartburn), and no prior surgeries or hospitalizations other than for childbirth. She has been advised by her doctor to lose weight. Socially, she works as a bank consultant, lives with her two children and partner in a supportive home environment, denies recent travel or sick contacts, is a non-smoker, and denies recreational drug use. She consumes 1-2 glasses of wine nightly but denies any issues with her alcohol intake. Her family history is notable for her father dying of a stroke in his 60s and her mother having gallstones.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aaj aapko Emergency Department mein kya takleef hai, zara bataiye?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नमस्ते, आपसे मिलकर बहुत अच्छा लगा, मुझे पेट के ऊपरी दाहिने हिस्से में दर्द हो रहा है।

Scenario: A female patient presents to the Emergency Department with a chief complaint of right upper quadrant abdominal pain. Her history of present illness details an insidious onset of sharp, localized pain in the right upper quadrant, just below the lungs, approximately three days prior, occurring 30-60 minutes after lunch. The pain has progressively worsened, becoming significantly more severe in the last 3-4 hours before presentation, now rated 8/10 in intensity. It does not radiate and remains confined to the right upper quadrant. She reports associated nausea over the past few days, which is worse today, but denies any vomiting, blood in emesis, skin changes, rashes, changes in urinary habits (dysuria, color changes), or changes in bowel patterns (diarrhea, color changes, blood in stool). Her energy levels are decreased today due to the pain, and her appetite is also significantly reduced today, though it was previously normal. Over-the-counter Advil and Tylenol provided no significant relief. She recalls a similar episode of pain a few years ago that resolved spontaneously without medical intervention. Her past medical history is largely unremarkable, with no known drug allergies, no prescribed medications (though she occasionally takes over-the-counter antacids a couple of times a month for heartburn), and no prior surgeries or hospitalizations other than for childbirth. She has been advised by her doctor to lose weight. Socially, she works as a bank consultant, lives with her two children and partner in a supportive home environment, denies recent travel or sick contacts, is a non-smoker, and denies recreational drug use. She consumes 1-2 glasses of wine nightly but denies any issues with her alcohol intake. Her family history is notable for her father dying of a stroke in his 60s and her mother having gallstones.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Kya aapko pehle bhi kabhi aisa kuch hua hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: मुझे लगता है कि यह कुछ साल पहले मेरे साथ हुआ था, जहाँ मुझे यह दर्द था और फिर यह अपने आप ठीक हो गया था, हालाँकि तब मैं आपातकालीन विभाग में नहीं गया था।

Scenario: A patient presents with a chief complaint of right upper quadrant abdominal pain, which began approximately 8 hours prior to presentation. The pain is described as an aching sensation, initially intermittent for the first 2 hours, but has become constant and unremitting for the past 5-6 hours, rated 8 out of 10 in severity. The pain is localized to the right upper abdomen and does not radiate. The patient reports no specific precipitating event, noting the pain started just before attempting to sleep. Eating sometimes exacerbates the pain, and the patient has noted a decreased appetite, eating less to avoid discomfort. Tylenol was attempted for pain relief without success. Associated symptoms include mild nausea and a feeling of slight fatigue, but the patient denies vomiting, fever, chills, sweats, changes in bowel habits (constipation, diarrhea, melena, hematochezia), changes in urinary patterns or color, skin rashes, or jaundice. The patient reports a history of similar, intermittent right upper quadrant pain that typically occurred after consuming fatty foods, which they previously attributed to indigestion. Past medical history is significant for diabetes, managed with metformin. The patient denies any known drug or environmental allergies. Surgical history includes wisdom teeth removal as a teenager, with no prior hospitalizations. Family history is notable for a father who experienced a myocardial infarction in his 60s, but the patient denies a family history of cancers or inflammatory bowel disease. Social history reveals the patient is currently unemployed due to COVID-19, lives alone in an apartment, and typically engages in regular running for exercise. The patient consumes 1-2 glasses of wine daily, denies tobacco use, and denies recreational drug use. No recent travel, infections, or sick contacts are reported.

The pain is localized to the right upper abdomen and does not radiate. The patient reports no specific precipitating event, noting the pain started just before attempting to sleep. Eating sometimes exacerbates the pain, and the patient has noted a decreased appetite, eating less to avoid discomfort. Tylenol was attempted for pain relief without success. Associated symptoms include mild nausea and a feeling of slight fatigue, but the patient denies vomiting, fever, chills, sweats, changes in bowel habits (constipation, diarrhea, melena, hematochezia), changes in urinary patterns or color, skin rashes, or jaundice. The patient reports a history of similar, intermittent right upper quadrant pain that typically occurred after consuming fatty foods, which they previously attributed to indigestion. Past medical history is significant for diabetes, managed with metformin. The patient denies any known drug or environmental allergies. Surgical history includes wisdom teeth removal as a teenager, with no prior hospitalizations. Family history is notable for a father who experienced a myocardial infarction in his 60s, but the patient denies a family history of cancers or inflammatory bowel disease. Social history reveals the patient is currently unemployed due to COVID-19, lives alone in an apartment, and typically engages in regular running for exercise. The patient consumes 1-2 glasses of wine daily, denies tobacco use, and denies recreational drug use. No recent travel, infections, or sick contacts are reported.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Dahine taraf, theek hai, aur aap bata sakte hain ki yeh kis tarah ka dard hai? Kya yeh halka dard hai, tez dard hai, ya khichav wala dard hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: मुझे लगता है कि यह एक दर्दनाक पीड़ा है, मैं ऐसा कहूंगा। यह शुरू में आती-जाती रहती थी, लेकिन अब यह बनी हुई है, जा नहीं रही है।

Scenario: A 20-something-year-old student presents with a chief complaint of diarrhea for the past three to four days, described as severe enough to cause her to miss classes due to embarrassment. This is a new onset for her, as she denies any similar past episodes. The diarrhea has been continuous, with stools consistently loose and brown in color, occurring approximately every hour, though she has lost count of the exact frequency. She reports no visible blood in her stool, though she admits to not looking closely. Associated symptoms include intermittent abdominal cramps that began yesterday, described as painful and coming and going, as well as on-and-off nausea and two episodes of watery, non-bloody vomiting yesterday, which she notes were less severe than the diarrhea. She reports feeling very tired but has not checked her temperature for fever or chills. She denies any changes in urine, discomfort with urination, rashes, or significant weight changes. Five days prior to symptom onset, she ate rice with chicken Manchurian at a new Chinese restaurant; her friend who accompanied her did not consume the same dish. She has attempted to manage her symptoms by drinking plenty of water to prevent dehydration but has not taken any over-the-counter medications. She has also been eating less, particularly since the onset of abdominal cramps yesterday. She denies recent travel or contact with sick individuals. Her past medical history is significant for asthma, for which she uses puffers, and she denies any known allergies or prior digestive issues. She underwent wisdom teeth removal in the past but was not hospitalized for it. Socially, she is a student living with two roommates, consumes 1-2 glasses of alcohol on weekends, and denies smoking or illicit substance use. Her typical diet includes oatmeal for breakfast, a quick lunch like a salad, and eating out for dinner, often a burger or fries. Family history reveals her brother had appendicitis when he was young, and her mother had a hysterectomy, but there is no other family history of digestive or abdominal problems.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Haan, main samajh sakta hoon ki aapko dast aa rahe hain, kya aap iske baare mein thoda bata sakte hain?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: जी हाँ, पिछले तीन-चार दिनों से मुझे दस्त हो रहे हैं और यह काफी गंभीर है, जिसकी वजह से मुझे अपनी कक्षाएं छोड़नी पड़ीं क्योंकि यह बहुत शर्मनाक था।

Scenario: A 20-something-year-old student presents with a chief complaint of diarrhea for the past three to four days, described as severe enough to cause her to miss classes due to embarrassment. This is a new onset for her, as she denies any similar past episodes. The diarrhea has been continuous, with stools consistently loose and brown in color, occurring approximately every hour, though she has lost count of the exact frequency. She reports no visible blood in her stool, though she admits to not looking closely. Associated symptoms include intermittent abdominal cramps that began yesterday, described as painful and coming and going, as well as on-and-off nausea and two episodes of watery, non-bloody vomiting yesterday, which she notes were less severe than the diarrhea. She reports feeling very tired but has not checked her temperature for fever or chills. She denies any changes in urine, discomfort with urination, rashes, or significant weight changes. Five days prior to symptom onset, she ate rice with chicken Manchurian at a new Chinese restaurant; her friend who accompanied her did not consume the same dish. She has attempted to manage her symptoms by drinking plenty of water to prevent dehydration but has not taken any over-the-counter medications. She has also been eating less, particularly since the onset of abdominal cramps yesterday. She denies recent travel or contact with sick individuals. Her past medical history is significant for asthma, for which she uses puffers, and she denies any known allergies or prior digestive issues. She underwent wisdom teeth removal in the past but was not hospitalized for it. Socially, she is a student living with two roommates, consumes 1-2 glasses of alcohol on weekends, and denies smoking or illicit substance use. Her typical diet includes oatmeal for breakfast, a quick lunch like a salad, and eating out for dinner, often a burger or fries. Family history reveals her brother had appendicitis when he was young, and her mother had a hysterectomy, but there is no other family history of digestive or abdominal problems.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Kya aapne apne vajan mein koi bada badlav mehsoos kiya hai, mujhe pata hai ki aap shayad roz vajan nahi karte honge, par kuch aisa jo aapko dikha ho?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: पिछले पाँच दिनों से मैंने अपना वज़न नहीं तौला है, इसलिए मुझे नहीं पता।

Scenario: A six-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of abdominal pain, vomiting, and fever. His mother reports that the abdominal pain began approximately three days prior to presentation, initially causing irritability, and is described as a generalized "stomach ache" located centrally, without specific tenderness on palpation. Two days prior to presentation, he developed vomiting, occurring a total of six times over the past two days; the first day's emesis contained food material after lunch, while yesterday's was described as yellowish, non-bilious, and non-bloody, occurring randomly after the initial episode. Concurrently, he developed watery diarrhea, with approximately six to seven episodes in the last day, also noted to be non-bloody. Yesterday, he developed a fever, measured at 38.3°C, accompanied by chills requiring multiple blankets, and exhibited significant lethargy, sleeping most of the day. He denies headaches, ear pain, eye pain, eye redness, runny nose, sore throat, dysphagia, anosmia, ageusia, cough, dyspnea, wheezing, chest pain, dysuria, urinary frequency, rashes, muscle aches, or joint pains. His diet has consisted strictly of home-cooked meals with no recent changes. He is a generally healthy child with no prior medical diagnoses, hospitalizations, or surgeries. His immunizations are up to date, and he has no known allergies or regular medications. Developmental milestones are met, and he performs well in school. Birth history is unremarkable, with a normal vaginal delivery at 39 weeks, an estimated birth weight of 3 kg, and normal Apgar scores. He lives with his mother, father, a 7-year-old brother, and a 10-year-old sister. No household contacts have been ill, and there is no recent travel history. He attended school last week. There are no concerns for home safety, no smoking in the household, and no pets. Family history is notable for a 10-year-old sister currently being evaluated for asthma, but otherwise, there is no family history of cardiac, pulmonary, congenital, genetic, celiac, or inflammatory bowel diseases. The mother inquired about the possibility of COVID-19 given the non-specific gastrointestinal symptoms.

Scenario: A six-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of abdominal pain, vomiting, and fever. His mother reports that the abdominal pain began approximately three days prior to presentation, initially causing irritability, and is described as a generalized "stomach ache" located centrally, without specific tenderness on palpation. Two days prior to presentation, he developed vomiting, occurring a total of six times over the past two days; the first day's emesis contained food material after lunch, while yesterday's was described as yellowish, non-bilious, and non-bloody, occurring randomly after the initial episode. Concurrently, he developed watery diarrhea, with approximately six to seven episodes in the last day, also noted to be non-bloody. Yesterday, he developed a fever, measured at 38.3°C, accompanied by chills requiring multiple blankets, and exhibited significant lethargy, sleeping most of the day. He denies headaches, ear pain, eye pain, eye redness, runny nose, sore throat, dysphagia, anosmia, ageusia, cough, dyspnea, wheezing, chest pain, dysuria, urinary frequency, rashes, muscle aches, or joint pains. His diet has consisted strictly of home-cooked meals with no recent changes. He is a generally healthy child with no prior medical diagnoses, hospitalizations, or surgeries. His immunizations are up to date, and he has no known allergies or regular medications. Developmental milestones are met, and he performs well in school. Birth history is unremarkable, with a normal vaginal delivery at 39 weeks, an estimated birth weight of 3 kg, and normal Apgar scores. He lives with his mother, father, a 7-year-old brother, and a 10-year-old sister. No household contacts have been ill, and there is no recent travel history. He attended school last week. There are no concerns for home safety, no smoking in the household, and no pets. Family history is notable for a 10-year-old sister currently being evaluated for asthma, but otherwise, there is no family history of cardiac, pulmonary, congenital, genetic, celiac, or inflammatory bowel diseases. The mother inquired about the possibility of COVID-19 given the non-specific gastrointestinal symptoms.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Achha, toh pehle koi medical diagnosis nahi tha?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नहीं, ऐसा कुछ भी नहीं है।

Scenario: A male patient, whose age is not specified but is a working production overseer and has two children, presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of worsening abdominal pain over the past three days. The patient reports an insidious onset of symptoms approximately five days prior, initially experiencing vague crampy sensations and bloating, which he attributed to constipation. His bowel habits, previously regular at once daily, shifted to constipation five days ago, with his last bowel movement occurring two days prior to presentation. The pain significantly intensified three days ago, localizing primarily to the right lower quadrant, near the right hip and inferior to the umbilicus, occasionally radiating slightly superior to the umbilicus but predominantly remaining in the right lower side. He describes the pain as progressively worsening, aggravated by palpation and a single episode of vomiting "the other day," which he found particularly distressing due to the associated bodily contractions. Resting flat provides minimal relief. Associated symptoms include nausea and a subjective sensation of feeling "a bit hot" recently, though no temperature was recorded. He denies any prior similar episodes of abdominal pain, recent sick contacts, or travel. His past medical history is significant for Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus, managed with Metformin for several years, which he states is generally well-controlled despite irregular self-monitoring of blood glucose. He denies any past surgical history apart from childhood dental extractions and confirms his appendix is intact. He reports no known drug allergies, though he experiences seasonal congestion in the fall. Socially, he resides in town with his wife and two children, one of whom is college-bound, and is employed as a production overseer. He consumes alcohol occasionally, primarily on special occasions or hot days (one to two beers), and denies any history of smoking, cannabis use, or other illicit substance use. Family history is notable for a grandmother who died of breast cancer at an early age, but he denies any family history of gastrointestinal disorders. He seeks an explanation for his persistent and worsening symptoms.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Toh, main samajh gaya hoon ki aapko kuch pet mein dard ho raha hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: हाँ, पेट में दर्द है, पिछले कुछ दिनों से, शायद 3 दिन पहले से, दर्द बढ़ गया है।

Scenario: A 30-year-old female, who works at a bank in London, presents with a chief complaint of suspected bladder infection, experiencing dysuria and increased urinary frequency for the past couple of days. She describes a burning or stinging sensation upon urination, which she notes has "maybe a little bit" worsened since onset, and an exacerbation of her baseline frequent urination, which typically occurs every 30-60 minutes due to a history of overactive bladder. She reports her urine has appeared "a little cloudy" but denies hematuria, frothy urine, or foul odor. Associated symptoms include feeling tired and a subjective sensation of being "a little hot" yesterday, without a measured fever, and her mother noted she looked "a little flushed." She denies any back pain, flank pain, vaginal lesions, or concerns for sexually transmitted infections, noting she has not been sexually active for several years. Scenario: A retired school teacher presents to the emergency department with a chief complaint of acute low back pain, which began suddenly yesterday while unloading groceries from his pickup truck. The pain is described as stabbing in the lower back, radiating as an aching sensation into his right leg. At rest, the pain is rated 2/10, but it significantly worsens with any movement, bending, or coughing, and has remained consistently severe since its onset. He reports a history of back pain over the years but states this episode is unprecedented in its intensity and character. He denies any associated symptoms such as weakness, fever, chills, night sweats, fatigue, skin changes, joint pain, cough, runny nose, changes in bowel or urinary habits, appetite changes, weight changes, recent infections, tingling, numbness, muscle weakness, erectile dysfunction, or bowel/bladder incontinence. He has no history of back trauma. His past medical history includes Type 2 Diabetes, for which he takes insulin, and a hemorrhoidectomy performed three years prior as a day surgery. He reports no known allergies. For the current pain, he has been taking Tylenol, which he states only "takes the edge off a little bit." Socially, he lives alone, occasionally consumes a glass of red wine on weekends, and has a significant smoking history of one pack of cigarettes per day for 40 years. He denies recreational drug use. His diet is described as normal and balanced, consisting mostly of home-cooked meals. He is sexually active with his girlfriend and reports having had two partners in the past year, consistently using condoms. Family history is notable for his father having prostate cancer.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aaj aapko emergency mein kya takleef hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: पीठ के निचले हिस्से में दर्द।

Scenario: A 26-year-old male presents with a chief complaint of diffuse, dull aching pain in his middle to lower back, rated 4-5/10, accompanied by significant morning stiffness lasting 30-60 minutes, which improves with activity. The pain and stiffness began insidiously approximately 4-5 months ago, progressively worsening over the last 5-6 months, without any identifiable preceding trauma or injury. He reports no radiation of the back pain. He has tried Tylenol without relief, but Advil provides some temporary alleviation, though morning stiffness and pain recur daily. Concurrently, he experiences intermittent, migratory arthralgias in his right knee and hands, which also started around six months ago. Associated symptoms include progressive fatigue and malaise, with some days feeling "burnt out." He denies fever, chills, night sweats, rashes, skin changes, nail changes, shortness of breath, changes in bowel or urinary patterns, changes in appetite or weight, vision problems, numbness, tingling, muscle weakness, or any localized redness or swelling in the affected areas. His past medical history is significant for asthma, managed with a PRN "blue inhaler," and a self-diagnosed episode of gastroenteritis several months prior, treated with antibiotics, following a buffet meal. He has environmental allergies to ragweed or pollen but no known drug allergies, and no history of hospitalizations or surgeries. Socially, he works at a bank, lives with his girlfriend in a condo, occasionally consumes alcohol (1-2 drinks on weekends), smokes marijuana 1-2 times per week, and denies cigarette smoking. He is sexually active with his girlfriend of six months, uses condoms mostly, and denies any history of sexually transmitted infections for himself or his partner, who is asymptomatic. Family history is notable for his mother having psoriasis, managed with topical creams, without reported associated joint pains.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Haan ji, toh kuch mahino se subah mein thodi akdan rehti hai, toh aapki kamar mein dard hai, bilkul sahi jagah bataiye kahan dard hota hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: मेरी पीठ में बहुत दर्द है, सुबह के समय मुझे बहुत अकड़न महसूस होती है और यह कुछ महीनों से चल रहा है।

He reports no radiation of the back pain. He has tried Tylenol without relief, but Advil provides some temporary alleviation, though morning stiffness and pain recur daily. Concurrently, he experiences intermittent, migratory arthralgias in his right knee and hands, which also started around six months ago. Associated symptoms include progressive fatigue and malaise, with some days feeling "burnt out." He denies fever, chills, night sweats, rashes, skin changes, nail changes, shortness of breath, changes in bowel or urinary patterns, changes in appetite or weight, vision problems, numbness, tingling, muscle weakness, or any localized redness or swelling in the affected areas. His past medical history is significant for asthma, managed with a PRN "blue inhaler," and a self-diagnosed episode of gastroenteritis several months prior, treated with antibiotics, following a buffet meal. He has environmental allergies to ragweed or pollen but no known drug allergies, and no history of hospitalizations or surgeries. Socially, he works at a bank, lives with his girlfriend in a condo, occasionally consumes alcohol (1-2 drinks on weekends), smokes marijuana 1-2 times per week, and denies cigarette smoking. He is sexually active with his girlfriend of six months, uses condoms mostly, and denies any history of sexually transmitted infections for himself or his partner, who is asymptomatic. Family history is notable for his mother having psoriasis, managed with topical creams, without reported associated joint pains.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Haan, yeh dard aapke gale tak aur kamar ke neeche tak hai, theek?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: मुझे पूरे शरीर में थोड़ा दर्द महसूस हो रहा है, किसी खास जगह पर ज़्यादा दर्द नहीं है, बल्कि मेरी पूरी पीठ में दर्द हो रहा है।

Scenario: A 30-year-old male software engineer, living alone, presents with a chief complaint of acute right ankle pain following an inversion injury sustained during a run yesterday evening. He reports stepping on an object, causing his right ankle to twist inwards. Immediately post-injury, the pain was mild, allowing him to complete his run and walk home. However, the pain progressively worsened over a few hours and has remained constant since. The pain is localized to the lateral aspect of the right ankle, with some radiation to the sole of the foot, and is described as dull and achy. It is aggravated by ankle movement and standing, and alleviated by rest. He denies any associated bruising, redness, swelling, skin changes, fever, chills, weakness, numbness, or tingling. He is able to bear weight for short periods and ambulate, though with pain, and can move his ankle slightly. His past medical history is notable for a similar ankle twist during childhood while playing basketball and a recent episode of diarrhea treated with a fluoroquinolone antibiotic a few months prior. He currently takes Vitamin D, Vitamin A, and other unspecified vitamins, and reports no known allergies, prior hospitalizations, or surgeries. Socially, he is a non-smoker, denies recreational drug use, and consumes alcohol infrequently (a glass of wine once every couple of months). He is actively training for a race, maintaining stable weight. His family history includes osteoarthritis in his grandparents and gout in his father.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aaj aap yahan kaise aaye hain?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नमस्ते, कल रात दौड़ते समय मेरा टखना मुड़ गया, मुझे लगता है कि मैं किसी चीज़ पर फिसल गया और अब बहुत दर्द हो रहा है।

Scenario: A 30-year-old male software engineer, living alone, presents with a chief complaint of acute right ankle pain following an inversion injury sustained during a run yesterday evening. He reports stepping on an object, causing his right ankle to twist inwards. Immediately post-injury, the pain was mild, allowing him to complete his run and walk home. However, the pain progressively worsened over a few hours and has remained constant since. The pain is localized to the lateral aspect of the right ankle, with some radiation to the sole of the foot, and is described as dull and achy. It is aggravated by ankle movement and standing, and alleviated by rest. He denies any associated bruising, redness, swelling, skin changes, fever, chills, weakness, numbness, or tingling. He is able to bear weight for short periods and ambulate, though with pain, and can move his ankle slightly. His past medical history is notable for a similar ankle twist during childhood while playing basketball and a recent episode of diarrhea treated with a fluoroquinolone antibiotic a few months prior. He currently takes Vitamin D, Vitamin A, and other unspecified vitamins, and reports no known allergies, prior hospitalizations, or surgeries. Socially, he is a non-smoker, denies recreational drug use, and consumes alcohol infrequently (a glass of wine once every couple of months). He is actively training for a race, maintaining stable weight. His family history includes osteoarthritis in his grandparents and gout in his father.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aur, sharab ke baare mein kya bataenge?

Scenario: A 40-year-old right-handed female presents with a chief complaint of right lateral elbow pain, which she first noticed several months ago with insidious onset and no specific trigger or trauma. The pain has been progressively worsening over this period, currently rated as a 4/10 on a pain scale. She describes the pain as primarily achy, with sharp exacerbations depending on movement. Aggravating factors include repetitive wrist movements, particularly wrist extension, picking up or holding heavy objects, and repetitive tasks associated with her occupation on an assembly line. The pain is alleviated by rest, over-the-counter analgesics such as ibuprofen and acetaminophen, and topical ointments, which provide some relief. The pain is localized to the lateral aspect of the right elbow and does not radiate. She denies any associated redness, swelling, warmth, misalignment, skin changes, deformities, numbness, tingling, or cold sensation in the affected arm. Furthermore, she reports no systemic symptoms such as weight loss, fever, chills, fatigue, rashes, changes in senses, cough, shortness of breath, wheezing, chest pain, palpitations, dizziness, changes in bowel or urinary habits, memory loss, or confusion. Despite the pain, she maintains full range of motion in her right elbow and hand and has been able to manage daily tasks and work, though the pain is increasingly becoming an issue with her job duties. On physical examination, there is tenderness to palpation at the lateral aspect of the right elbow, but no tenderness medially, in the forearm, or biceps. Pain is elicited with wrist extension and wrist flexion when the elbow is in full extension, but not with elbow flexion, shoulder extension or abduction, or forearm pronation and supination. Her past medical history is notable only for a non-emergency C-section 17 years prior; she reports being otherwise healthy with no other hospitalizations or surgeries, is up to date on immunizations, and has no known allergies. Current medications include only acetaminophen and ibuprofen as needed for pain. Socially, she works on an assembly line, consumes alcohol occasionally (one glass of wine per week), has never smoked, denies marijuana use, has had no recent sick contacts or travel. Her family history is negative for any skeletal, muscular, neurological, or autoimmune conditions.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aapko kya takleef hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नमस्ते, मुझे पिछले कुछ महीनों से दाहिनी कोहनी के बाहरी हिस्से में दर्द हो रहा है, जो हाल ही में और बढ़ गया है।

Scenario: A male patient presents with a chief complaint of intense right buttock pain, which has recently (last 2 days) begun to radiate down his right leg. He reports a history of intermittent buttock pain, but the current episode is significantly more severe, rated 8/10, and persistent, though exacerbated by walking, sitting, and any movement, with relief only when staying still. He describes the pain as sharp in the buttock and burning down the leg, consistent with a radicular pattern. Associated symptoms include subjective right leg weakness, difficulty walking, and an observed antalgic gait, along with numbness and tingling down the posterior aspect of the right leg. He denies urinary or stool incontinence, sexual dysfunction, or groin numbness. He has a history of similar "sciatic pain" in the past, attributed to his occupation as a truck driver involving prolonged sitting, but denies any recent trauma. Over-the-counter Advil and Tylenol have provided minimal relief. His past medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolemia, for which he takes amlodipine and a statin, along with a multivitamin; he reports no known allergies and is up-to-date on immunizations. Socially, he is a truck driver who frequently undertakes long-haul trips, lives with his wife and son, smokes approximately half a pack of cigarettes daily for 40 years (having previously smoked more), and consumes 1-2 beers per weekend. He denies marijuana or other recreational drug use, recent sick contacts, or travel outside of work-related driving. Family history is negative for musculoskeletal, neurological, autoimmune conditions, or cancers. Review of systems is otherwise negative for joint pains, muscle aches, weight loss, fevers, chills, rashes, changes in vision, hearing, smell, taste, cough, shortness of breath, wheezing, chest pain, palpitations, dizziness, fainting spells, changes in bowel movements (diarrhea, constipation, blood in stool), nausea, vomiting, or changes in urine. On physical examination, inspection of the right buttock and leg reveals no swelling, redness, heat, skin changes, atrophy, or deformity. He exhibits an antalgic gait, favoring his left leg. Palpation elicits tenderness over the right buttock area, but no pain over the right hip bone, posterior legs, or anterior thighs. Range of motion testing reveals pain with standing from a sitting position (hip and knee extension), right hip flexion, and right foot dorsiflexion, but no pain with knee flexion, right foot plantarflexion, right hip abduction, or right hip adduction.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Aapko kya takleef hai?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: मुझे दाहिने नितंब (buttock) क्षेत्र में तेज दर्द हो रहा है, और हाल ही में यह दर्द मेरे दाहिने पैर में भी फैल रहा है।

Scenario: A male patient presents with a chief complaint of intense right buttock pain, which has recently (last 2 days) begun to radiate down his right leg. He reports a history of intermittent buttock pain, but the current episode is significantly more severe, rated 8/10, and persistent, though exacerbated by walking, sitting, and any movement, with relief only when staying still. He describes the pain as sharp in the buttock and burning down the leg, consistent with a radicular pattern. Associated symptoms include subjective right leg weakness, difficulty walking, and an observed antalgic gait, along with numbness and tingling down the posterior aspect of the right leg. He denies urinary or stool incontinence, sexual dysfunction, or groin numbness. He has a history of similar "sciatic pain" in the past, attributed to his occupation as a truck driver involving prolonged sitting, but denies any recent trauma. Over-the-counter Advil and Tylenol have provided minimal relief. His past medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolemia, for which he takes amlodipine and a statin, along with a multivitamin; he reports no known allergies and is up-to-date on immunizations. Socially, he is a truck driver who frequently undertakes long-haul trips, lives with his wife and son, smokes approximately half a pack of cigarettes daily for 40 years (having previously smoked more), and consumes 1-2 beers per weekend. He denies marijuana or other recreational drug use, recent sick contacts, or travel outside of work-related driving. Family history is negative for musculoskeletal, neurological, autoimmune conditions, or cancers. Review of systems is otherwise negative for joint pains, muscle aches, weight loss, fevers, chills, rashes, changes in vision, hearing, smell, taste, cough, shortness of breath, wheezing, chest pain, palpitations, dizziness, fainting spells, changes in bowel movements (diarrhea, constipation, blood in stool), nausea, vomiting, or changes in urine. On physical examination, inspection of the right buttock and leg reveals no swelling, redness, heat, skin changes, atrophy, or deformity. He exhibits an antalgic gait, favoring his left leg. Palpation elicits tenderness over the right buttock area, but no pain over the right hip bone, posterior legs, or anterior thighs. Range of motion testing reveals pain with standing from a sitting position (hip and knee extension), right hip flexion, and right foot dorsiflexion, but no pain with knee flexion, right foot plantarflexion, right hip abduction, or right hip adduction.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Achha, theek hai, aur yeh sirf aapke right leg mein hai, theek hai?

Scenario: A patient presents with a chief complaint of left elbow pain, which has been ongoing for approximately three months, with a significant worsening over the past three weeks. The pain is localized to the medial aspect of the left elbow, described as typically achey but occasionally sharp, and rates as a 5 out of 10 in severity. There is no reported radiation of the pain. Aggravating factors include full elbow extension, pronation, resisted wrist flexion, and passive wrist extension, with the pain notably exacerbated after long shifts at work. Alleviating factors include temporary relief with over-the-counter NSAIDs. The patient denies any specific precipitating trauma or fall, and reports no prior injuries to the left elbow. Associated symptoms such as fever, chills, night sweats, weight loss, headaches, sensory changes, eye/ear symptoms, upper respiratory symptoms, cough, shortness of breath, wheezing, chest pain, lightheadedness, dizziness, palpitations, gastrointestinal symptoms, urinary problems, skin rashes, numbness, tingling, muscle weakness, other joint pains, memory changes, confusion, fatigue, or appetite changes are all denied. The patient's past medical history is unremarkable, with no chronic medical conditions. Current medications include only multivitamins, and there are no known drug allergies. The patient reports a history of a right humerus fracture in childhood, which healed without complications. Socially, the patient lives with a partner in an apartment and is employed on an assembly line for Chrysler, a job involving repetitive tasks. Hobbies previously included golf, but this has been ceased for the past six months due to the elbow pain. The patient is a non-smoker, consumes a glass of wine every other day, and smokes cannabis once a week. Family history is negative for heart, lung, musculoskeletal, neurological, or autoimmune diseases such as thyroid disorders or diabetes. Upon verbal assessment, the patient reports no visible swelling, redness, muscle atrophy, misalignment, joint deformity, or scars on the elbow. There is point tenderness over the medial epicondyle of the left elbow and slight pain over the olecranon, but no pain over the lateral elbow, forearm, biceps, or triceps muscles. The joint does not feel hot. While there is pain with full elbow extension, shoulder movements are pain-free with a full range of motion. Pain is elicited with pronation, resisted wrist flexion, and passive wrist extension. No numbness or tingling is reported.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Main aapki kya madad kar sakta hoon?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नमस्ते, हाँ, मुझे पिछले कुछ हफ़्तों से मेरे बाएँ कोहनी में दर्द हो रहा है और यह ठीक नहीं हो रहा है, इसलिए मैं यह पता लगाने के लिए यहाँ हूँ कि यह क्या है।

Scenario: A patient presents with a chief complaint of left elbow pain, which has been ongoing for approximately three months, with a significant worsening over the past three weeks. The pain is localized to the medial aspect of the left elbow, described as typically achey but occasionally sharp, and rates as a 5 out of 10 in severity. There is no reported radiation of the pain. Aggravating factors include full elbow extension, pronation, resisted wrist flexion, and passive wrist extension, with the pain notably exacerbated after long shifts at work. Alleviating factors include temporary relief with over-the-counter NSAIDs. The patient denies any specific precipitating trauma or fall, and reports no prior injuries to the left elbow. Associated symptoms such as fever, chills, night sweats, weight loss, headaches, sensory changes, eye/ear symptoms, upper respiratory symptoms, cough, shortness of breath, wheezing, chest pain, lightheadedness, dizziness, palpitations, gastrointestinal symptoms, urinary problems, skin rashes, numbness, tingling, muscle weakness, other joint pains, memory changes, confusion, fatigue, or appetite changes are all denied. The patient's past medical history is unremarkable, with no chronic medical conditions. Current medications include only multivitamins, and there are no known drug allergies. The patient reports a history of a right humerus fracture in childhood, which healed without complications. Socially, the patient lives with a partner in an apartment and is employed on an assembly line for Chrysler, a job involving repetitive tasks. Hobbies previously included golf, but this has been ceased for the past six months due to the elbow pain. The patient is a non-smoker, consumes a glass of wine every other day, and smokes cannabis once a week. Family history is negative for heart, lung, musculoskeletal, neurological, or autoimmune diseases such as thyroid disorders or diabetes. Upon verbal assessment, the patient reports no visible swelling, redness, muscle atrophy, misalignment, joint deformity, or scars on the elbow. There is point tenderness over the medial epicondyle of the left elbow and slight pain over the olecranon, but no pain over the lateral elbow, forearm, biceps, or triceps muscles. The joint does not feel hot. While there is pain with full elbow extension, shoulder movements are pain-free with a full range of motion. Pain is elicited with pronation, resisted wrist flexion, and passive wrist extension. No numbness or tingling is reported.

Patient_Responses_Hindi: नहीं, मैं बस कुछ मल्टीविटामिन लेती हूँ।

Scenario: A patient presents with a chief complaint of left elbow pain, which has been ongoing for approximately three months, with a significant worsening over the past three weeks. The pain is localized to the medial aspect of the left elbow, described as typically achey but occasionally sharp, and rates as a 5 out of 10 in severity. There is no reported radiation of the pain. Aggravating factors include full elbow extension, pronation, resisted wrist flexion, and passive wrist extension, with the pain notably exacerbated after long shifts at work. Alleviating factors include temporary relief with over-the-counter NSAIDs. The patient denies any specific precipitating trauma or fall, and reports no prior injuries to the left elbow. Associated symptoms such as fever, chills, night sweats, weight loss, headaches, sensory changes, eye/ear symptoms, upper respiratory symptoms, cough, shortness of breath, wheezing, chest pain, lightheadedness, dizziness, palpitations, gastrointestinal symptoms, urinary problems, skin rashes, numbness, tingling, muscle weakness, other joint pains, memory changes, confusion, fatigue, or appetite changes are all denied. The patient's past medical history is unremarkable, with no chronic medical conditions. Current medications include only multivitamins, and there are no known drug allergies. The patient reports a history of a right humerus fracture in childhood, which healed without complications. Socially, the patient lives with a partner in an apartment and is employed on an assembly line for Chrysler, a job involving repetitive tasks. Hobbies previously included golf, but this has been ceased for the past six months due to the elbow pain. The patient is a non-smoker, consumes a glass of wine every other day, and smokes cannabis once a week. Family history is negative for heart, lung, musculoskeletal, neurological, or autoimmune diseases such as thyroid disorders or diabetes. Upon verbal assessment, the patient reports no visible swelling, redness, muscle atrophy, misalignment, joint deformity, or scars on the elbow. There is point tenderness over the medial epicondyle of the left elbow and slight pain over the olecranon, but no pain over the lateral elbow, forearm, biceps, or triceps muscles. The joint does not feel hot. While there is pain with full elbow extension, shoulder movements are pain-free with a full range of motion. Pain is elicited with pronation, resisted wrist flexion, and passive wrist extension. No numbness or tingling is reported.

Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: आपके कोहनी के अंदरूनी हिस्से में पिछले कुछ महीनों से दर्द और कुछ शारीरिक जांच के नतीजों को देखते हुए, जैसे कि कलाई को पीछे की ओर मोड़ने पर, कलाई को आगे की ओर मोड़ने पर प्रतिरोध होने पर, और कोहनी के अंदरूनी हिस्से में छूने पर दर्द होना, यह मेडियल एपिकॉन्डिलाइटिस या उस क्षेत्र में टेंडिनोपैथी हो सकती है, जिसका इलाज आमतौर पर गतिविधियों में बदलाव करके, जैसे दर्द पैदा करने वाले दोहराव वाले कामों से बचकर, Advil और Tylenol जैसी दवाएं लेकर, और फिजियोथेरेपिस्ट से सीखे गए या खुद से किए जाने वाले स्ट्रेचिंग और मजबूती वाले व्यायामों से किया जाता है, साथ ही कोहनी के अंदरूनी हिस्से में अल्नर लिगामेंट की चोट भी हो सकती है, और अगर दर्द ठीक नहीं होता है तो अल्ट्रासाउंड कराने पर विचार किया जा सकता है।
Patient_Responses_Hindi: नहीं, वह हो गया। आपको क्या लगता है मुझे क्या बीमारी है और इसे कैसे ठीक किया जा सकता है?

Scenario: A 17-year-old male, currently in his last year of Grade 12, presents with a chief complaint of acute right knee pain, redness, and swelling, which began two days prior following a direct kick to the medial aspect of his right knee during a soccer game. The pain, described as sharp and rated 5/10 in severity, has remained constant or slightly worsened since the injury. It is localized to the medial aspect of the right knee, without radiation, and is aggravated by direct pressure, excessive knee flexion or extension, and varus or valgus stress, with valgus stress eliciting a sensation of slight joint opening. Alleviation is achieved with ice application. Associated symptoms include mild swelling and redness over the medial aspect of the right knee, and slight difficulty with ambulation or instability only during extreme knee flexion or extension; he denies hearing a "pop" sound at the time of injury. A comprehensive review of systems was negative for headaches, sensory changes, ocular or otic symptoms, rhinorrhea, sore throat, cough, dyspnea, wheezing, chest pain, palpitations, syncope, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, appetite changes, unexpected weight loss, abdominal pain, changes in bowel or urinary habits, skin rashes, other joint pains, fatigue, numbness, tingling, or muscle weakness. His past medical history is unremarkable, with no known medical conditions, medication allergies, current medications, prior surgeries, or hospitalizations. Socially, he lives with his parents and three siblings, plays both soccer and football, denies tobacco, alcohol, or recreational drug use, and is sexually active in a monogamous relationship of one year, with both partners having been tested for sexually transmitted infections and no concern for pregnancy. He denies recent exposure to sick contacts. Family history is negative for musculoskeletal or neurological conditions. On physical examination, inspection revealed redness and slight swelling on the medial aspect of the right knee, without ecchymosis, muscle atrophy, misalignment, or joint deformities. Gait was normal, though painful. Palpation revealed no increased temperature but marked tenderness along the medial joint line. Stress testing elicited pain with varus stress on the medial aspect and pain with a slight sensation of joint opening with valgus stress on the medial aspect. There was no anterior or posterior tibial instability. Range of motion of the knee, hip, and ankle was full. Neurological examination was unremarkable for numbness, tingling, muscle weakness, or sensory changes, and reflexes were noted as normal. The clinical picture is suggestive of a medial collateral ligament (MCL) strain or injury, with medial meniscal injury or bursitis as differential diagnoses, and conservative management with NSAIDs, ice, and physical therapy was recommended, with an X-ray to be considered if symptoms do not improve.
Doctor_Questions_Hinglish: Main aapki kya madad kar sakta hoon?
Patient_Responses_Hindi: हाल ही में फुटबॉल खेलते समय मेरे दाहिने घुटने के अंदरूनी हिस्से में चोट लगने के कारण दर्द हो रहा है, और वह थोड़ा लाल और सूजा हुआ भी दिख रहा है।
